Sam Altman deserves credit for YC's turn toward hard tech. When he became CEO in 2014 he went out and recruited companies doing stuff like airliners and fusion, and hard tech startups have been some of the best in every batch since.

@rohitdayanii Starting an AI research nonprofit as a side project?

Hard tech was not the cool trend in 2014. The reason he did it was mostly that he had a personal interest in it. Before I convinced him to take over YC, he was going to start a company making nuclear reactors.

But this weird obsession of Sam's ended up being very useful for Y Combinator, because by the time hard tech became cool, we had lots of experience funding hard tech companies, and lots of battle-scarred alumni who could advise new startups doing it.

In retrospect it was an instance of what I always advise young founders to do. If you're young, your needs predict future demand, so gratify your random interests, because in fact they're far from random. Sam was living in the future and built what was missing.

@thinkingman44 If I had to say when hard tech became cool among investors, it was probably when A16z funded Anduril in 2019. But that was 5 long years later. Before that, hard tech startups often had a really hard time raising money.

@Rob1Ham My understanding is the bug was discovered by a white hat and hence not actually exploited . I think there is still ambiguity though bc it happened in the shielded pool perhaps @mert can chime in

And just to be clear I think it’s very good that Zcash is pushing the envelope both in privacy and post quantum. The frontier is unforgiving but I’m glad they are doing it.

